09/11/2004
ANKARA, Turkey -- During a phone conversation with US President George W. Bush on Monday (8 November), Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan called for increased security measures in Iraq. Erdogan praised the level of co-operation between Ankara and Washington, expressing hope for its continuation during Bush's second term in office. 
In other news, the situation in Kirkuk, northern Iraq, is the expected focus of talks between Turkish officials and visiting Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. Both Turkey and Syria oppose the political aspirations of Iraqi Kurds in Kirkuk. (NTV, The Daily Star - 09/11/04) 
